#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "=== Account Setup and Configuration\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:6
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(((GitHub, user accounts)))\n"
"The first thing you need to do is set up a free user account.\n"
"Simply visit https://github.com[], choose a user name that isn't already taken, provide an email address and a password, and click the big green \"`Sign up for GitHub`\" button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:9
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The GitHub sign-up form\n"
"image::images/signup.png[The GitHub sign-up form]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:13
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The next thing you'll see is the pricing page for upgraded plans, but it's safe to ignore this for now.\n"
"GitHub will send you an email to verify the address you provided.\n"
"Go ahead and do this; it's pretty important (as we'll see later).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:15
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:46
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:12
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:143
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:471
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:34
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[NOTE]\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "GitHub provides almost all of its functionality with free accounts, except some advanced features.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:20
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GitHub's paid plans include advanced tools and features as well as increased limits for free services, but we won't be covering those in this book.\n"
"To get more information about available plans and their comparison, visit https://github.com/pricing[].\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:24
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Clicking the Octocat logo at the top-left of the screen will take you to your dashboard page.\n"
"You're now ready to use GitHub.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:26
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== SSH Access\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:30
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(((SSH keys, with GitHub)))\n"
"As of right now, you're fully able to connect with Git repositories using the `https://` protocol, authenticating with the username and password you just set up.\n"
"However, to simply clone public projects, you don't even need to sign up - the account we just created comes into play when we fork projects and push to our forks a bit later.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:34
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you'd like to use SSH remotes, you'll need to configure a public key.\n"
"If you don't already have one, see <<ch04-git-on-the-server#_generate_ssh_key>>.\n"
"Open up your account settings using the link at the top-right of the window:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:37
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The \"`Account settings`\" link\n"
"image::images/account-settings.png[The âAccount settingsâ link]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then select the \"`SSH keys`\" section along the left-hand side.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:42
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The \"`SSH keys`\" link.\n"
"image::images/ssh-keys.png[The âSSH keysâ link]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:44
#, no-wrap
msgid "From there, click the \"`Add an SSH key`\" button, give your key a name, paste the contents of your `~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub` (or whatever you named it) public-key file into the text area, and click \"`Add key`\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:49
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Be sure to name your SSH key something you can remember.\n"
"You can name each of your keys (e.g. \"My Laptop\" or \"Work Account\") so that if you need to revoke a key later, you can easily tell which one you're looking for.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:53
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_personal_avatar]]\n"
"==== Your Avatar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:56
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Next, if you wish, you can replace the avatar that is generated for you with an image of your choosing.\n"
"First go to the \"`Profile`\" tab (above the SSH Keys tab) and click \"`Upload new picture`\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:59
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The \"`Profile`\" link\n"
"image::images/your-profile.png[The âProfileâ link]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "We'll choose a copy of the Git logo that is on our hard drive and then we get a chance to crop it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:64
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Crop your avatar\n"
"image::images/avatar-crop.png[Crop your uploaded avatar]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now anywhere you interact on the site, people will see your avatar next to your username.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:68
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you happen to have uploaded an avatar to the popular Gravatar service (often used for Wordpress accounts), that avatar will be used by default and you don't need to do this step.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Your Email Addresses\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:73
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The way that GitHub maps your Git commits to your user is by email address.\n"
"If you use multiple email addresses in your commits and you want GitHub to link them up properly, you need to add all the email addresses you have used to the Emails section of the admin section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:77
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_add_email_addresses]]\n"
".Add email addresses\n"
"image::images/email-settings.png[Add all your email addresses]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:83
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In <<_add_email_addresses>> we can see some of the different states that are possible.\n"
"The top address is verified and set as the primary address, meaning that is where you'll get any notifications and receipts.\n"
"The second address is verified and so can be set as the primary if you wish to switch them.\n"
"The final address is unverified, meaning that you can't make it your primary address.\n"
"If GitHub sees any of these in commit messages in any repository on the site, it will be linked to your user now.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Two Factor Authentication\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Finally, for extra security, you should definitely set up Two-factor Authentication or \"`2FA`\".\n"
"Two-factor Authentication is an authentication mechanism that is becoming more and more popular recently to mitigate the risk of your account being compromised if your password is stolen somehow.\n"
"Turning it on will make GitHub ask you for two different methods of authentication, so that if one of them is compromised, an attacker will not be able to access your account.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can find the Two-factor Authentication setup under the Security tab of your Account settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:94
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".2FA in the Security Tab\n"
"image::images/2fa-1.png[2FA in the Security Tab]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you click on the \"`Set up two-factor authentication`\" button, it will take you to a configuration page where you can choose to use a phone app to generate your secondary code (a \"`time based one-time password`\"), or you can have GitHub send you a code via SMS each time you need to log in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/1-setting-up-account.asc:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "After you choose which method you prefer and follow the instructions for setting up 2FA, your account will then be a little more secure and you will have to provide a code in addition to your password whenever you log into GitHub.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "=== Contributing to a Project\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:4
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that our account is set up, let's walk through some details that could be useful in helping you contribute to an existing project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Forking Projects\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:10
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(((forking)))\n"
"If you want to contribute to an existing project to which you don't have push access, you can \"`fork`\" the project.\n"
"When you \"`fork`\" a project, GitHub will make a copy of the project that is entirely yours; it lives in your namespace, and you can push to it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:15
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Historically, the term \"`fork`\" has been somewhat negative in context, meaning that someone took an open source project in a different direction, sometimes creating a competing project and splitting the contributors.\n"
"In GitHub, a \"`fork`\" is simply the same project in your own namespace, allowing you to make changes to a project publicly as a way to contribute in a more open manner.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:20
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This way, projects don't have to worry about adding users as collaborators to give them push access.\n"
"People can fork a project, push to it, and contribute their changes back to the original repository by creating what's called a Pull Request, which we'll cover next.\n"
"This opens up a discussion thread with code review, and the owner and the contributor can then communicate about the change until the owner is happy with it, at which point the owner can merge it in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:22
#, no-wrap
msgid "To fork a project, visit the project page and click the \"`Fork`\" button at the top-right of the page.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:25
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The \"`Fork`\" button\n"
"image::images/forkbutton.png[The âForkâ button]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "After a few seconds, you'll be taken to your new project page, with your own writeable copy of the code.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:31
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[ch06-github_flow]]\n"
"==== The GitHub Flow\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:36
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(((GitHub, Flow)))\n"
"GitHub is designed around a particular collaboration workflow, centered on Pull Requests.\n"
"This flow works whether you're collaborating with a tightly-knit team in a single shared repository, or a globally-distributed company or network of strangers contributing to a project through dozens of forks.\n"
"It is centered on the <<ch03-git-branching#_topic_branch>> workflow covered in <<ch03-git-branching#ch03-git-branching>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "Here's how it generally works:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Fork the project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Create a topic branch from `master`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Make some commits to improve the project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Push this branch to your GitHub project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Open a Pull Request on GitHub.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Discuss, and optionally continue committing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '7. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "The project owner merges or closes the Pull Request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '8. '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sync the updated master back to your fork.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is basically the Integration Manager workflow covered in <<ch05-distributed-git#_integration_manager>>, but instead of using email to communicate and review changes, teams use GitHub's web based tools.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "Let's walk through an example of proposing a change to an open source project hosted on GitHub using this flow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:53
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[TIP]\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:57
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can use the official *GitHub CLI* tool instead of the GitHub web interface for most things.\n"
"The tool can be used on Windows, MacOS, and Linux systems.\n"
"Go to the https://cli.github.com/[GitHub CLI homepage] for installation instructions and the manual.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Creating a Pull Request\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "Tony is looking for code to run on his Arduino programmable microcontroller and has found a great program file on GitHub at https://github.com/schacon/blink[].\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:65
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The project we want to contribute to\n"
"image::images/blink-01-start.png[The project we want to contribute to]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:69
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The only problem is that the blinking rate is too fast.\n"
"We think it's much nicer to wait 3 seconds instead of 1 in between each state change.\n"
"So let's improve the program and submit it back to the project as a proposed change.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:73
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"First, we click the 'Fork' button as mentioned earlier to get our own copy of the project.\n"
"Our user name here is \"`tonychacon`\" so our copy of this project is at `https://github.com/tonychacon/blink` and that's where we can edit it.\n"
"We will clone it locally, create a topic branch, make the code change and finally push that change back up to GitHub.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:75
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:248
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:508
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:522
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:538
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:91
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:134
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:158
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:197
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:210
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[source,console]\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:78
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git clone https://github.com/tonychacon/blink <1>\n"
"Cloning into 'blink'...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:82
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ cd blink\n"
"$ git checkout -b slow-blink <2>\n"
"Switched to a new branch 'slow-blink'\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:86
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sed -i '' 's/1000/3000/' blink.ino (macOS) <3>\n"
"# If you're on a Linux system, do this instead:\n"
"# $ sed -i 's/1000/3000/' blink.ino <3>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git diff --word-diff <4>\n"
"diff --git a/blink.ino b/blink.ino\n"
"index 15b9911..a6cc5a5 100644\n"
"--- a/blink.ino\n"
"+++ b/blink.ino\n"
"@@ -18,7 +18,7 @@ void setup() {\n"
"// the loop routine runs over and over again forever:\n"
"void loop() {\n"
"  digitalWrite(led, HIGH);   // turn the LED on (HIGH is the voltage level)\n"
"  [-delay(1000);-]{+delay(3000);+}               // wait for a second\n"
"  digitalWrite(led, LOW);    // turn the LED off by making the voltage LOW\n"
"  [-delay(1000);-]{+delay(3000);+}               // wait for a second\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:104
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git commit -a -m 'Change delay to 3 seconds' <5>\n"
"[slow-blink 5ca509d] Change delay to 3 seconds\n"
" 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:115
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git push origin slow-blink <6>\n"
"Username for 'https://github.com': tonychacon\n"
"Password for 'https://tonychacon@github.com':\n"
"Counting objects: 5, done.\n"
"Delta compression using up to 8 threads.\n"
"Compressing objects: 100% (3/3), done.\n"
"Writing objects: 100% (3/3), 340 bytes | 0 bytes/s, done.\n"
"Total 3 (delta 1), reused 0 (delta 0)\n"
"To https://github.com/tonychacon/blink\n"
" * [new branch]      slow-blink -> slow-blink\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<1> Clone our fork of the project locally.\n"
"<2> Create a descriptive topic branch.\n"
"<3> Make our change to the code.\n"
"<4> Check that the change is good.\n"
"<5> Commit our change to the topic branch.\n"
"<6> Push our new topic branch back up to our GitHub fork.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:125
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now if we go back to our fork on GitHub, we can see that GitHub noticed that we pushed a new topic branch up and presents us with a big green button to check out our changes and open a Pull Request to the original project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:127
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can alternatively go to the \"`Branches`\" page at `\\https://github.com/<user>/<project>/branches` to locate your branch and open a new Pull Request from there.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:130
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Pull Request button\n"
"image::images/blink-02-pr.png[Pull Request button]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(((GitHub, pull requests)))\n"
"If we click that green button, we'll see a screen that asks us to give our Pull Request a title and description.\n"
"It is almost always worthwhile to put some effort into this, since a good description helps the owner of the original project determine what you were trying to do, whether your proposed changes are correct, and whether accepting the changes would improve the original project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:136
#, no-wrap
msgid "We also see a list of the commits in our topic branch that are \"`ahead`\" of the `master` branch (in this case, just the one) and a unified diff of all the changes that will be made should this branch get merged by the project owner.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:139
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Pull Request creation page\n"
"image::images/blink-03-pull-request-open.png[Pull Request creation]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:141
#, no-wrap
msgid "When you hit the 'Create pull request' button on this screen, the owner of the project you forked will get a notification that someone is suggesting a change and will link to a page that has all of this information on it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:146
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Though Pull Requests are used commonly for public projects like this when the contributor has a complete change ready to be made, it's also often used in internal projects _at the beginning_ of the development cycle.\n"
"Since you can keep pushing to the topic branch even *after* the Pull Request is opened, it's often opened early and used as a way to iterate on work as a team within a context, rather than opened at the very end of the process.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:149
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Iterating on a Pull Request\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:152
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"At this point, the project owner can look at the suggested change and merge it, reject it or comment on it.\n"
"Let's say that he likes the idea, but would prefer a slightly longer time for the light to be off than on.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:155
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Where this conversation may take place over email in the workflows presented in <<ch05-distributed-git#ch05-distributed-git>>, on GitHub this happens online.\n"
"The project owner can review the unified diff and leave a comment by clicking on any of the lines.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:158
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Comment on a specific line of code in a Pull Request\n"
"image::images/blink-04-pr-comment.png[PR line comment]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:161
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once the maintainer makes this comment, the person who opened the Pull Request (and indeed, anyone else watching the repository) will get a notification.\n"
"We'll go over customizing this later, but if he had email notifications turned on, Tony would get an email like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:165
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_email_notification]]\n"
".Comments sent as email notifications\n"
"image::images/blink-04-email.png[Email notification]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:169
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Anyone can also leave general comments on the Pull Request.\n"
"In <<_pr_discussion>> we can see an example of the project owner both commenting on a line of code and then leaving a general comment in the discussion section.\n"
"You can see that the code comments are brought into the conversation as well.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:173
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_discussion]]\n"
".Pull Request discussion page\n"
"image::images/blink-05-general-comment.png[PR discussion page]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:178
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now the contributor can see what they need to do in order to get their change accepted.\n"
"Luckily this is very straightforward.\n"
"Where over email you may have to re-roll your series and resubmit it to the mailing list, with GitHub you simply commit to the topic branch again and push, which will automatically update the Pull Request.\n"
"In <<_pr_final>> you can also see that the old code comment has been collapsed in the updated Pull Request, since it was made on a line that has since been changed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:180
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adding commits to an existing Pull Request doesn't trigger a notification, so once Tony has pushed his corrections he decides to leave a comment to inform the project owner that he made the requested change.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:184
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_final]]\n"
".Pull Request final\n"
"image::images/blink-06-final.png[PR final]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:188
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"An interesting thing to notice is that if you click on the \"`Files Changed`\" tab on this Pull Request, you'll get the \"`unified`\" diff -- that is, the total aggregate difference that would be introduced to your main branch if this topic branch was merged in.\n"
"In `git diff` terms, it basically automatically shows you `git diff master...<branch>` for the branch this Pull Request is based on.\n"
"See <<ch05-distributed-git#_what_is_introduced>> for more about this type of diff.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:192
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The other thing you'll notice is that GitHub checks to see if the Pull Request merges cleanly and provides a button to do the merge for you on the server.\n"
"This button only shows up if you have write access to the repository and a trivial merge is possible.\n"
"If you click it GitHub will perform a \"`non-fast-forward`\" merge, meaning that even if the merge *could* be a fast-forward, it will still create a merge commit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:195
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you would prefer, you can simply pull the branch down and merge it locally.\n"
"If you merge this branch into the `master` branch and push it to GitHub, the Pull Request will automatically be closed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is the basic workflow that most GitHub projects use.\n"
"Topic branches are created, Pull Requests are opened on them, a discussion ensues, possibly more work is done on the branch and eventually the request is either closed or merged.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:201
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[NOTE]\n"
".Not Only Forks\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:205
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It's important to note that you can also open a Pull Request between two branches in the same repository.\n"
"If you're working on a feature with someone and you both have write access to the project, you can push a topic branch to the repository and open a Pull Request on it to the `master` branch of that same project to initiate the code review and discussion process.\n"
"No forking necessary.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:208
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Advanced Pull Requests\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:210
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that we've covered the basics of contributing to a project on GitHub, let's cover a few interesting tips and tricks about Pull Requests so you can be more effective in using them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:212
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Pull Requests as Patches\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:215
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It's important to understand that many projects don't really think of Pull Requests as queues of perfect patches that should apply cleanly in order, as most mailing list-based projects think of patch series contributions.\n"
"Most GitHub projects think about Pull Request branches as iterative conversations around a proposed change, culminating in a unified diff that is applied by merging.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:219
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is an important distinction, because generally the change is suggested before the code is thought to be perfect, which is far more rare with mailing list based patch series contributions.\n"
"This enables an earlier conversation with the maintainers so that arriving at the proper solution is more of a community effort.\n"
"When code is proposed with a Pull Request and the maintainers or community suggest a change, the patch series is generally not re-rolled, but instead the difference is pushed as a new commit to the branch, moving the conversation forward with the context of the previous work intact.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:224
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For instance, if you go back and look again at <<_pr_final>>, you'll notice that the contributor did not rebase his commit and send another Pull Request.\n"
"Instead they added new commits and pushed them to the existing branch.\n"
"This way if you go back and look at this Pull Request in the future, you can easily find all of the context of why decisions were made.\n"
"Pushing the \"`Merge`\" button on the site purposefully creates a merge commit that references the Pull Request so that it's easy to go back and research the original conversation if necessary.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:226
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Keeping up with Upstream\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:229
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If your Pull Request becomes out of date or otherwise doesn't merge cleanly, you will want to fix it so the maintainer can easily merge it.\n"
"GitHub will test this for you and let you know at the bottom of every Pull Request if the merge is trivial or not.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:233
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_fail]]\n"
".Pull Request does not merge cleanly\n"
"image::images/pr-01-fail.png[PR merge failure]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:235
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you see something like <<_pr_fail>>, you'll want to fix your branch so that it turns green and the maintainer doesn't have to do extra work.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:238
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You have two main options in order to do this.\n"
"You can either rebase your branch on top of whatever the target branch is (normally the `master` branch of the repository you forked), or you can merge the target branch into your branch.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:241
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Most developers on GitHub will choose to do the latter, for the same reasons we just went over in the previous section.\n"
"What matters is the history and the final merge, so rebasing isn't getting you much other than a slightly cleaner history and in return is *far* more difficult and error prone.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:243
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you want to merge in the target branch to make your Pull Request mergeable, you would add the original repository as a new remote, fetch from it, merge the main branch of that repository into your topic branch, fix any issues and finally push it back up to the same branch you opened the Pull Request on.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:246
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For example, let's say that in the \"`tonychacon`\" example we were using before, the original author made a change that would create a conflict in the Pull Request.\n"
"Let's go through those steps.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:250
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ git remote add upstream https://github.com/schacon/blink <1>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:258
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git fetch upstream <2>\n"
"remote: Counting objects: 3, done.\n"
"remote: Compressing objects: 100% (3/3), done.\n"
"Unpacking objects: 100% (3/3), done.\n"
"remote: Total 3 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0)\n"
"From https://github.com/schacon/blink\n"
" * [new branch]      master     -> upstream/master\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:263
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git merge upstream/master <3>\n"
"Auto-merging blink.ino\n"
"CONFLICT (content): Merge conflict in blink.ino\n"
"Automatic merge failed; fix conflicts and then commit the result.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:269
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ vim blink.ino <4>\n"
"$ git add blink.ino\n"
"$ git commit\n"
"[slow-blink 3c8d735] Merge remote-tracking branch 'upstream/master' \\\n"
"    into slower-blink\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:278
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git push origin slow-blink <5>\n"
"Counting objects: 6, done.\n"
"Delta compression using up to 8 threads.\n"
"Compressing objects: 100% (6/6), done.\n"
"Writing objects: 100% (6/6), 682 bytes | 0 bytes/s, done.\n"
"Total 6 (delta 2), reused 0 (delta 0)\n"
"To https://github.com/tonychacon/blink\n"
"   ef4725c..3c8d735  slower-blink -> slow-blink\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:285
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<1> Add the original repository as a remote named `upstream`.\n"
"<2> Fetch the newest work from that remote.\n"
"<3> Merge the main branch of that repository into your topic branch.\n"
"<4> Fix the conflict that occurred.\n"
"<5> Push back up to the same topic branch.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:287
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you do that, the Pull Request will be automatically updated and re-checked to see if it merges cleanly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:291
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_merge_fix]]\n"
".Pull Request now merges cleanly\n"
"image::images/pr-02-merge-fix.png[PR fixed]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:294
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One of the great things about Git is that you can do that continuously.\n"
"If you have a very long-running project, you can easily merge from the target branch over and over again and only have to deal with conflicts that have arisen since the last time that you merged, making the process very manageable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:298
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you absolutely wish to rebase the branch to clean it up, you can certainly do so, but it is highly encouraged to not force push over the branch that the Pull Request is already opened on.\n"
"If other people have pulled it down and done more work on it, you run into all of the issues outlined in <<ch03-git-branching#_rebase_peril>>.\n"
"Instead, push the rebased branch to a new branch on GitHub and open a brand new Pull Request referencing the old one, then close the original.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:300
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== References\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:303
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Your next question may be \"`How do I reference the old Pull Request?`\".\n"
"It turns out there are many, many ways to reference other things almost anywhere you can write in GitHub.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:309
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's start with how to cross-reference another Pull Request or an Issue.\n"
"All Pull Requests and Issues are assigned numbers and they are unique within the project.\n"
"For example, you can't have Pull Request +#3+ _and_ Issue +#3+.\n"
"If you want to reference any Pull Request or Issue from any other one, you can simply put `+#<num>+` in any comment or description.\n"
"You can also be more specific if the Issue or Pull request lives somewhere else; write `username#<num>` if you're referring to an Issue or Pull Request in a fork of the repository you're in, or `username/repo#<num>` to reference something in another repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:314
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's look at an example.\n"
"Say we rebased the branch in the previous example, created a new pull request for it, and now we want to reference the old pull request from the new one.\n"
"We also want to reference an issue in the fork of the repository and an issue in a completely different project.\n"
"We can fill out the description just like <<_pr_references>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:318
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_references]]\n"
".Cross references in a Pull Request\n"
"image::images/mentions-01-syntax.png[PR references]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:320
#, no-wrap
msgid "When we submit this pull request, we'll see all of that rendered like <<_pr_references_render>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:324
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_references_render]]\n"
".Cross references rendered in a Pull Request\n"
"image::images/mentions-02-render.png[PR references rendered]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:326
#, no-wrap
msgid "Notice that the full GitHub URL we put in there was shortened to just the information needed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:330
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now if Tony goes back and closes out the original Pull Request, we can see that by mentioning it in the new one, GitHub has automatically created a trackback event in the Pull Request timeline.\n"
"This means that anyone who visits this Pull Request and sees that it is closed can easily link back to the one that superseded it.\n"
"The link will look something like <<_pr_closed>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:334
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_closed]]\n"
".Link back to the new Pull Request in the closed Pull Request timeline\n"
"image::images/mentions-03-closed.png[PR closed]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:338
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In addition to issue numbers, you can also reference a specific commit by SHA-1.\n"
"You have to specify a full 40 character SHA-1, but if GitHub sees that in a comment, it will link directly to the commit.\n"
"Again, you can reference commits in forks or other repositories in the same way you did with issues.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:340
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== GitHub Flavored Markdown\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:344
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linking to other Issues is just the beginning of interesting things you can do with almost any text box on GitHub.\n"
"In  Issue and Pull Request descriptions, comments, code comments and more, you can use what is called \"`GitHub Flavored Markdown`\".\n"
"Markdown is like writing in plain text but which is rendered richly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:346
#, no-wrap
msgid "See <<_example_markdown>> for an example of how comments or text can be written and then rendered using Markdown.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:350
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_example_markdown]]\n"
".An example of GitHub Flavored Markdown as written and as rendered\n"
"image::images/markdown-01-example.png[Example Markdown]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:353
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The GitHub flavor of Markdown adds more things you can do beyond the basic Markdown syntax.\n"
"These can all be really useful when creating useful Pull Request or Issue comments or descriptions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:355
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Task Lists\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:359
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The first really useful GitHub specific Markdown feature, especially for use in Pull Requests, is the Task List.\n"
"A task list is a list of checkboxes of things you want to get done.\n"
"Putting them into an Issue or Pull Request normally indicates things that you want to get done before you consider the item complete.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:361
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can create a task list like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:363
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:398
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:423
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:451
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:497
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[source,text]\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:367
#, no-wrap
msgid "[X] Write the code\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:367
#, no-wrap
msgid "[ ] Write all the tests\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:367
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"- [ ] Document the code\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:370
#, no-wrap
msgid "If we include this in the description of our Pull Request or Issue, we'll see it rendered like <<_eg_task_lists>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:374
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_eg_task_lists]]\n"
".Task lists rendered in a Markdown comment\n"
"image::images/markdown-02-tasks.png[Example Task List]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:377
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is often used in Pull Requests to indicate what all you would like to get done on the branch before the Pull Request will be ready to merge.\n"
"The really cool part is that you can simply click the checkboxes to update the comment -- you don't have to edit the Markdown directly to check tasks off.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:382
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"What's more, GitHub will look for task lists in your Issues and Pull Requests and show them as metadata on the pages that list them out.\n"
"For example, if you have a Pull Request with tasks and you look at the overview page of all Pull Requests, you can see how far done it is.\n"
"This helps people break down Pull Requests into subtasks and helps other people track the progress of the branch.\n"
"You can see an example of this in <<_task_list_progress>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:386
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_task_list_progress]]\n"
".Task list summary in the Pull Request list\n"
"image::images/markdown-03-task-summary.png[Example Task List]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:388
#, no-wrap
msgid "These are incredibly useful when you open a Pull Request early and use it to track your progress through the implementation of the feature.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:390
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Code Snippets\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:394
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also add code snippets to comments.\n"
"This is especially useful if you want to present something that you _could_ try to do before actually implementing it as a commit on your branch.\n"
"This is also often used to add example code of what is not working or what this Pull Request could implement.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:396
#, no-wrap
msgid "To add a snippet of code you have to \"`fence`\" it in backticks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:405
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```java\n"
"for(int i=0 ; i < 5 ; i++)\n"
"{\n"
"   System.out.println(\"i is : \" + i);\n"
"}\n"
"```\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:409
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you add a language name like we did there with 'java', GitHub will also try to syntax highlight the snippet.\n"
"In the case of the above example, it would end up rendering like <<_md_code>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:413
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_md_code]]\n"
".Rendered fenced code example\n"
"image::images/markdown-04-fenced-code.png[Rendered fenced code]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:415
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Quoting\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:419
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're responding to a small part of a long comment, you can selectively quote out of the other comment by preceding the lines with the `>` character.\n"
"In fact, this is so common and so useful that there is a keyboard shortcut for it.\n"
"If you highlight text in a comment that you want to directly reply to and hit the `r` key, it will quote that text in the comment box for you.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:421
#, no-wrap
msgid "The quotes look something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:426
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"> Whether 'tis Nobler in the mind to suffer\n"
"> The Slings and Arrows of outrageous Fortune,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:428
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"How big are these slings and in particular, these arrows?\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:431
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once rendered, the comment will look like <<_md_quote>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:435
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_md_quote]]\n"
".Rendered quoting example\n"
"image::images/markdown-05-quote.png[Rendered quoting]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:437
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Emoji\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:442
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Finally, you can also use emoji in your comments.\n"
"This is actually used quite extensively in comments you see on many GitHub Issues and Pull Requests.\n"
"There is even an emoji helper in GitHub.\n"
"If you are typing a comment and you start with a `:` character, an autocompleter will help you find what you're looking for.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:446
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_md_emoji_auto]]\n"
".Emoji autocompleter in action\n"
"image::images/markdown-06-emoji-complete.png[Emoji autocompleter]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:449
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Emojis take the form of `:<name>:` anywhere in the comment.\n"
"For instance, you could write something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:453
#, no-wrap
msgid "I :eyes: that :bug: and I :cold_sweat:.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:455
#, no-wrap
msgid ":trophy: for :microscope: it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:457
#, no-wrap
msgid ":+1: and :sparkles: on this :ship:, it's :fire::poop:!\n"
