#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:492
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_fetch_and_push_on_different_repositories]]\n"
"==== Keep your GitHub public repository up-to-date\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:495
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once you've forked a GitHub repository, your repository (your \"fork\") exists independently from the original.\n"
"In particular, when the original repository has new commits, GitHub informs you by a message like:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:499
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This branch is 5 commits behind progit:master.\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:503
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"But your GitHub repository will never be automatically updated by GitHub; this is something that you must do yourself.\n"
"Fortunately, this is very easy to do.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:506
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"One possibility to do this requires no configuration.\n"
"For example, if you forked from `https://github.com/progit/progit2.git`, you can keep your `master` branch up-to-date like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:512
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git checkout master <1>\n"
"$ git pull https://github.com/progit/progit2.git <2>\n"
"$ git push origin master <3>\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:517
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<1> If you were on another branch, return to `master`.\n"
"<2> Fetch changes from `https://github.com/progit/progit2.git` and merge them into `master`.\n"
"<3> Push your `master` branch to `origin`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:520
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This works, but it is a little tedious having to spell out the fetch URL every time.\n"
"You can automate this work with a bit of configuration:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:527
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git remote add progit https://github.com/progit/progit2.git <1>\n"
"$ git fetch progit <2>\n"
"$ git branch --set-upstream-to=progit/master master <3>\n"
"$ git config --local remote.pushDefault origin <4>\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:534
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<1> Add the source repository and give it a name.\n"
"    Here, I have chosen to call it `progit`.\n"
"<2> Get a reference on progit's branches, in particular `master`.\n"
"<3> Set your `master` branch to fetch from the `progit` remote.\n"
"<4> Define the default push repository to `origin`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:536
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once this is done, the workflow becomes much simpler:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:542
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git checkout master <1>\n"
"$ git pull <2>\n"
"$ git push <3>\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:547
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<1> If you were on another branch, return to `master`.\n"
"<2> Fetch changes from `progit` and merge changes into `master`.\n"
"<3> Push your `master` branch to `origin`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/2-contributing.asc:550
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This approach can be useful, but it's not without downsides.\n"
"Git will happily do this work for you silently, but it won't warn you if you make a commit to `master`, pull from `progit`, then push to `origin` -- all of those operations are valid with this setup.\n"
"So you'll have to take care never to commit directly to `master`, since that branch effectively belongs to the upstream repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:3
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_maintaining_gh_project]]\n"
"=== Maintaining a Project\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:5
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that we're comfortable contributing to a project, let's look at the other side: creating, maintaining and administering your own project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:7
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Creating a New Repository\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:10
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's create a new repository to share our project code with.\n"
"Start by clicking the \"`New repository`\" button on the right-hand side of the dashboard, or from the `+` button in the top toolbar next to your username as seen in <<_new_repo_dropdown>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:13
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The \"`Your repositories`\" area\n"
"image::images/newrepo.png[The âYour repositoriesâ area]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:17
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_new_repo_dropdown]]\n"
".The \"`New repository`\" dropdown\n"
"image::images/new-repo.png[The ânew repositoryâ dropdown]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "This takes you to the \"`new repository`\" form:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:22
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The \"`new repository`\" form\n"
"image::images/newrepoform.png[The ânew repositoryâ form]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:25
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"All you really have to do here is provide a project name; the rest of the fields are completely optional.\n"
"For now, just click the \"`Create Repository`\" button, and boom â you have a new repository on GitHub, named `<user>/<project_name>`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:28
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Since you have no code there yet, GitHub will show you instructions for how to create a brand-new Git repository, or connect an existing Git project.\n"
"We won't belabor this here; if you need a refresher, check out <<ch02-git-basics-chapter#ch02-git-basics-chapter>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:32
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now that your project is hosted on GitHub, you can give the URL to anyone you want to share your project with.\n"
"Every project on GitHub is accessible over HTTPS as `\\https://github.com/<user>/<project_name>`, and over SSH as `\\git@github.com:<user>/<project_name>`.\n"
"Git can fetch from and push to both of these URLs, but they are access-controlled based on the credentials of the user connecting to them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:38
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It is often preferable to share the HTTPS based URL for a public project, since the user does not have to have a GitHub account to access it for cloning.\n"
"Users will have to have an account and an uploaded SSH key to access your project if you give them the SSH URL.\n"
"The HTTPS one is also exactly the same URL they would paste into a browser to view the project there.\n"
"====\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Adding Collaborators\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:45
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
