".Repository collaborators\n"
"image::images/collaborators.png[The repository collaborators box]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Managing Pull Requests\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that you have a project with some code in it and maybe even a few collaborators who also have push access, let's go over what to do when you get a Pull Request yourself.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:65
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Pull Requests can either come from a branch in a fork of your repository or they can come from another branch in the same repository.\n"
"The only difference is that the ones in a fork are often from people where you can't push to their branch and they can't push to yours, whereas with internal Pull Requests generally both parties can access the branch.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "For these examples, let's assume you are \"`tonychacon`\" and you've created a new Arduino code project named \"`fade`\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_email_notifications]]\n"
"===== Email Notifications\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:73
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Someone comes along and makes a change to your code and sends you a Pull Request.\n"
"You should get an email notifying you about the new Pull Request and it should look something like <<_email_pr>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:77
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_email_pr]]\n"
".Email notification of a new Pull Request\n"
"image::images/maint-01-email.png[Pull Request email notification]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:82
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are a few things to notice about this email.\n"
"It will give you a small diffstat -- a list of files that have changed in the Pull Request and by how much.\n"
"It gives you a link to the Pull Request on GitHub.\n"
"It also gives you a few URLs that you can use from the command line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:86
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you notice the line that says `git pull <url> patch-1`, this is a simple way to merge in a remote branch without having to add a remote.\n"
"We went over this quickly in <<ch05-distributed-git#_checking_out_remotes>>.\n"
"If you wish, you can create and switch to a topic branch and then run this command to merge in the Pull Request changes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The other interesting URLs are the `.diff` and `.patch` URLs, which as you may guess, provide unified diff and patch versions of the Pull Request.\n"
"You could technically merge in the Pull Request work with something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:93
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ curl https://github.com/tonychacon/fade/pull/1.patch | git am\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Collaborating on the Pull Request\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:99
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As we covered in <<ch06-github#ch06-github_flow>>, you can now have a conversation with the person who opened the Pull Request.\n"
"You can comment on specific lines of code, comment on whole commits or comment on the entire Pull Request itself, using GitHub Flavored Markdown everywhere.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:102
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Every time someone else comments on the Pull Request you will continue to get email notifications so you know there is activity happening.\n"
"They will each have a link to the Pull Request where the activity is happening and you can also directly respond to the email to comment on the Pull Request thread.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:105
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Responses to emails are included in the thread\n"
"image::images/maint-03-email-resp.png[Email response]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once the code is in a place you like and want to merge it in, you can either pull the code down and merge it locally, either with the `git pull <url> <branch>` syntax we saw earlier, or by adding the fork as a remote and fetching and merging.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:112
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If the merge is trivial, you can also just hit the \"`Merge`\" button on the GitHub site.\n"
"This will do a \"`non-fast-forward`\" merge, creating a merge commit even if a fast-forward merge was possible.\n"
"This means that no matter what, every time you hit the merge button, a merge commit is created.\n"
"As you can see in <<_merge_button>>, GitHub gives you all of this information if you click the hint link.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:116
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_merge_button]]\n"
".Merge button and instructions for merging a Pull Request manually\n"
"image::images/maint-02-merge.png[Merge button]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you decide you don't want to merge it, you can also just close the Pull Request and the person who opened it will be notified.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:121
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_refs]]\n"
"===== Pull Request Refs\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:124
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're dealing with a *lot* of Pull Requests and don't want to add a bunch of remotes or do one time pulls every time, there is a neat trick that GitHub allows you to do.\n"
"This is a bit of an advanced trick and we'll go over the details of this a bit more in <<ch10-git-internals#_refspec>>, but it can be pretty useful.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GitHub actually advertises the Pull Request branches for a repository as sort of pseudo-branches on the server.\n"
"By default you don't get them when you clone, but they are there in an obscured way and you can access them pretty easily.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:130
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To demonstrate this, we're going to use a low-level command (often referred to as a \"`plumbing`\" command, which we'll read about more in <<ch10-git-internals#_plumbing_porcelain>>) called `ls-remote`.\n"
"This command is generally not used in day-to-day Git operations but it's useful to show us what references are present on the server.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:132
#, no-wrap
msgid "If we run this command against the \"`blink`\" repository we were using earlier, we will get a list of all the branches and tags and other references in the repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:144
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git ls-remote https://github.com/schacon/blink\n"
"10d539600d86723087810ec636870a504f4fee4d\tHEAD\n"
"10d539600d86723087810ec636870a504f4fee4d\trefs/heads/master\n"
"6a83107c62950be9453aac297bb0193fd743cd6e\trefs/pull/1/head\n"
"afe83c2d1a70674c9505cc1d8b7d380d5e076ed3\trefs/pull/1/merge\n"
"3c8d735ee16296c242be7a9742ebfbc2665adec1\trefs/pull/2/head\n"
"15c9f4f80973a2758462ab2066b6ad9fe8dcf03d\trefs/pull/2/merge\n"
"a5a7751a33b7e86c5e9bb07b26001bb17d775d1a\trefs/pull/4/head\n"
"31a45fc257e8433c8d8804e3e848cf61c9d3166c\trefs/pull/4/merge\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:147
#, no-wrap
msgid "Of course, if you're in your repository and you run `git ls-remote origin` or whatever remote you want to check, it will show you something similar to this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:150
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If the repository is on GitHub and you have any Pull Requests that have been opened, you'll get these references that are prefixed with `refs/pull/`.\n"
"These are basically branches, but since they're not under `refs/heads/` you don't get them normally when you clone or fetch from the server -- the process of fetching ignores them normally.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:154
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are two references per Pull Request - the one that ends in `/head` points to exactly the same commit as the last commit in the Pull Request branch.\n"
"So if someone opens a Pull Request in our repository and their branch is named `bug-fix` and it points to commit `a5a775`, then in *our* repository we will not have a `bug-fix` branch (since that's in their fork), but we _will_ have `pull/<pr#>/head` that points to `a5a775`.\n"
"This means that we can pretty easily pull down every Pull Request branch in one go without having to add a bunch of remotes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:156
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now, you could do something like fetching the reference directly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:162
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git fetch origin refs/pull/958/head\n"
"From https://github.com/libgit2/libgit2\n"
" * branch            refs/pull/958/head -> FETCH_HEAD\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:168
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This tells Git, \"`Connect to the `origin` remote, and download the ref named `refs/pull/958/head`.`\"\n"
"Git happily obeys, and downloads everything you need to construct that ref, and puts a pointer to the commit you want under `.git/FETCH_HEAD`.\n"
"You can follow that up with `git merge FETCH_HEAD` into a branch you want to test it in, but that merge commit message looks a bit weird.\n"
"Also, if you're reviewing a *lot* of pull requests, this gets tedious.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:172
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There's also a way to fetch _all_ of the pull requests, and keep them up to date whenever you connect to the remote.\n"
"Open up `.git/config` in your favorite editor, and look for the `origin` remote.\n"
"It should look a bit like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:174
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:186
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[source,ini]\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:178
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[remote \"origin\"]\n"
"    url = https://github.com/libgit2/libgit2\n"
"    fetch = +refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/origin/*\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:184
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"That line that begins with `fetch =` is a \"`refspec.`\"\n"
"It's a way of mapping names on the remote with names in your local `.git` directory.\n"
"This particular one tells Git, \"the things on the remote that are under `refs/heads` should go in my local repository under `refs/remotes/origin`.\"\n"
"You can modify this section to add another refspec:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:191
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[remote \"origin\"]\n"
"    url = https://github.com/libgit2/libgit2.git\n"
"    fetch = +refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/origin/*\n"
"    fetch = +refs/pull/*/head:refs/remotes/origin/pr/*\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:195
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"That last line tells Git, \"`All the refs that look like `refs/pull/123/head` should be stored locally like `refs/remotes/origin/pr/123`.`\"\n"
"Now, if you save that file, and do a `git fetch`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:204
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git fetch\n"
"# â¦\n"
" * [new ref]         refs/pull/1/head -> origin/pr/1\n"
" * [new ref]         refs/pull/2/head -> origin/pr/2\n"
" * [new ref]         refs/pull/4/head -> origin/pr/4\n"
"# â¦\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:208
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Now all of the remote pull requests are represented locally with refs that act much like tracking branches; they're read-only, and they update when you do a fetch.\n"
"This makes it super easy to try the code from a pull request locally:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:215
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ git checkout pr/2\n"
"Checking out files: 100% (3769/3769), done.\n"
"Branch pr/2 set up to track remote branch pr/2 from origin.\n"
"Switched to a new branch 'pr/2'\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:220
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The eagle-eyed among you would note the `head` on the end of the remote portion of the refspec.\n"
"There's also a `refs/pull/#/merge` ref on the GitHub side, which represents the commit that would result if you push the \"`merge`\" button on the site.\n"
"This can allow you to test the merge before even hitting the button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:223
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Pull Requests on Pull Requests\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:226
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Not only can you open Pull Requests that target the main or `master` branch, you can actually open a Pull Request targeting any branch in the network.\n"
"In fact, you can even target another Pull Request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:228
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you see a Pull Request that is moving in the right direction and you have an idea for a change that depends on it or you're not sure is a good idea, or you just don't have push access to the target branch, you can open a Pull Request directly to it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:231
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When you go to open a Pull Request, there is a box at the top of the page that specifies which branch you're requesting to pull to and which you're requesting to pull from.\n"
"If you hit the \"`Edit`\" button at the right of that box you can change not only the branches but also which fork.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:235
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_pr_targets]]\n"
".Manually change the Pull Request target fork and branch\n"
"image::images/maint-04-target.png[PR targets]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:237
#, no-wrap
msgid "Here you can fairly easily specify to merge your new branch into another Pull Request or another fork of the project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:239
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Mentions and Notifications\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:241
#, no-wrap
msgid "GitHub also has a pretty nice notifications system built in that can come in handy when you have questions or need feedback from specific individuals or teams.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:243
#, no-wrap
msgid "In any comment you can start typing a `@` character and it will begin to autocomplete with the names and usernames of people who are collaborators or contributors in the project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:246
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Start typing @ to mention someone\n"
"image::images/maint-05-mentions.png[Mentions]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:248
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can also mention a user who is not in that dropdown, but often the autocompleter can make it faster.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:252
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once you post a comment with a user mention, that user will be notified.\n"
"This means that this can be a really effective way of pulling people into conversations rather than making them poll.\n"
"Very often in  Pull Requests on GitHub people will pull in other people on their teams or in their company to review an Issue or Pull Request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:256
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If someone gets mentioned on a Pull Request or Issue, they will be \"`subscribed`\" to it and will continue getting notifications any time some activity occurs on it.\n"
"You will also be subscribed to something if you opened it, if you're watching the repository or if you comment on something.\n"
"If you no longer wish to receive notifications, there is an \"`Unsubscribe`\" button on the page you can click to stop receiving updates on it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:259
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Unsubscribe from an Issue or Pull Request\n"
"image::images/maint-06-unsubscribe.png[Unsubscribe]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:261
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== The Notifications Page\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:264
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When we mention \"`notifications`\" here with respect to GitHub, we mean a specific way that GitHub tries to get in touch with you when events happen and there are a few different ways you can configure them.\n"
"If you go to the \"`Notification center`\" tab from the settings page, you can see some of the options you have.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:267
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".Notification center options\n"
"image::images/maint-07-notifications.png[Notification center]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:269
#, no-wrap
msgid "The two choices are to get notifications over \"`Email`\" and over \"`Web`\" and you can choose either, neither or both for when you actively participate in things and for activity on repositories you are watching.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:271
#, no-wrap
msgid "====== Web Notifications\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:274
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Web notifications only exist on GitHub and you can only check them on GitHub.\n"
"If you have this option selected in your preferences and a notification is triggered for you, you will see a small blue dot over your notifications icon at the top of your screen as seen in <<_not_center>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:278
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_not_center]]\n"
".Notification center\n"
"image::images/maint-08-notifications-page.png[Notification center]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:283
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you click on that, you will see a list of all the items you have been notified about, grouped by project.\n"
"You can filter to the notifications of a specific project by clicking on its name in the left hand sidebar.\n"
"You can also acknowledge the notification by clicking the checkmark icon next to any notification, or acknowledge _all_ of the notifications in a project by clicking the checkmark at the top of the group.\n"
"There is also a mute button next to each checkmark that you can click to not receive any further notifications on that item.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:286
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"All of these tools are very useful for handling large numbers of notifications.\n"
"Many GitHub power users will simply turn off email notifications entirely and manage all of their notifications through this screen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:288
#, no-wrap
msgid "====== Email Notifications\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:293
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Email notifications are the other way you can handle notifications through GitHub.\n"
"If you have this turned on you will get emails for each notification.\n"
"We saw examples of this in <<_email_notification>> and <<_email_pr>>.\n"
"The emails will also be threaded properly, which is nice if you're using a threading email client.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:295
#, no-wrap
msgid "There is also a fair amount of metadata embedded in the headers of the emails that GitHub sends you, which can be really helpful for setting up custom filters and rules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:297
#, no-wrap
msgid "For instance, if we look at the actual email headers sent to Tony in the email shown in <<_email_pr>>, we will see the following among the information sent:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:299
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[source,mbox]\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:309
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To: tonychacon/fade <fade@noreply.github.com>\n"
"Message-ID: <tonychacon/fade/pull/1@github.com>\n"
"Subject: [fade] Wait longer to see the dimming effect better (#1)\n"
"X-GitHub-Recipient: tonychacon\n"
"List-ID: tonychacon/fade <fade.tonychacon.github.com>\n"
"List-Archive: https://github.com/tonychacon/fade\n"
"List-Post: <mailto:reply+i-4XXX@reply.github.com>\n"
"List-Unsubscribe: <mailto:unsub+i-XXX@reply.github.com>,...\n"
"X-GitHub-Recipient-Address: tchacon@example.com\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:314
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are a couple of interesting things here.\n"
"If you want to highlight or re-route emails to this particular project or even Pull Request, the information in `Message-ID` gives you all the data in `<user>/<project>/<type>/<id>` format.\n"
"If this were an issue, for example, the `<type>` field would have been \"`issues`\" rather than \"`pull`\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:317
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The `List-Post` and `List-Unsubscribe` fields mean that if you have a mail client that understands those, you can easily post to the list or \"`Unsubscribe`\" from the thread.\n"
"That would be essentially the same as clicking the \"`mute`\" button on the web version of the notification or \"`Unsubscribe`\" on the Issue or Pull Request page itself.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:319
#, no-wrap
msgid "It's also worth noting that if you have both email and web notifications enabled and you read the email version of the notification, the web version will be marked as read as well if you have images allowed in your mail client.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:321
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Special Files\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:323
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are a couple of special files that GitHub will notice if they are present in your repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:325
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== README\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:329
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The first is the `README` file, which can be of nearly any format that GitHub recognizes as prose.\n"
"For example, it could be `README`, `README.md`, `README.asciidoc`, etc.\n"
"If GitHub sees a README file in your source, it will render it on the landing page of the project.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:332
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Many teams use this file to hold all the relevant project information for someone who might be new to the repository or project.\n"
"This generally includes things like:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:338
#, no-wrap
msgid "What the project is for\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:338
#, no-wrap
msgid "How to configure and install it\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:338
#, no-wrap
msgid "An example of how to use it or get it running\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:338
#, no-wrap
msgid "The license that the project is offered under\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:338
#, no-wrap
msgid "How to contribute to it\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:340
#, no-wrap
msgid "Since GitHub will render this file, you can embed images or links in it for added ease of understanding.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:342
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== CONTRIBUTING\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:345
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The other special file that GitHub recognizes is the `CONTRIBUTING` file.\n"
"If you have a file named `CONTRIBUTING` with any file extension, GitHub will show <<_contrib_file>> when anyone starts opening a Pull Request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:349
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_contrib_file]]\n"
".Opening a Pull Request when a CONTRIBUTING file exists\n"
"image::images/maint-09-contrib.png[Contributing notice]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:352
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The idea here is that you can specify specific things you want or don't want in a Pull Request sent to your project.\n"
"This way people may actually read the guidelines before opening the Pull Request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:354
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Project Administration\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:356
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generally there are not a lot of administrative things you can do with a single project, but there are a couple of items that might be of interest.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:358
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Changing the Default Branch\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:360
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you are using a branch other than \"`master`\" as your default branch that you want people to open Pull Requests on or see by default, you can change that in your repository's settings page under the \"`Options`\" tab.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:364
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_default_branch]]\n"
".Change the default branch for a project\n"
"image::images/maint-10-default-branch.png[Default branch]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:366
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simply change the default branch in the dropdown and that will be the default for all major operations from then on, including which branch is checked out by default when someone clones the repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:368
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Transferring a Project\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:370
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you would like to transfer a project to another user or an organization in GitHub, there is a \"`Transfer ownership`\" option at the bottom of the same \"`Options`\" tab of your repository settings page that allows you to do this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:374
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_transfer_project]]\n"
".Transfer a project to another GitHub user or Organization\n"
"image::images/maint-11-transfer.png[Transfer]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:376
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is helpful if you are abandoning a project and someone wants to take it over, or if your project is getting bigger and want to move it into an organization.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/3-maintaining.asc:378
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Not only does this move the repository along with all its watchers and stars to another place, it also sets up a redirect from your URL to the new place.\n"
"It will also redirect clones and fetches from Git, not just web requests.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:3
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[ch06-github_orgs]]\n"
"=== Managing an organization\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:9
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(((GitHub, organizations)))\n"
"In addition to single-user accounts, GitHub has what are called Organizations.\n"
"Like personal accounts, Organizational accounts have a namespace where all their projects exist, but many other things are different.\n"
"These accounts represent a group of people with shared ownership of projects, and there are many tools to manage subgroups of those people.\n"
"Normally these accounts are used for Open Source groups (such as \"`perl`\" or \"`rails`\") or companies (such as \"`google`\" or \"`twitter`\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Organization Basics\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:13
#, no-wrap
msgid "An organization is pretty easy to create; just click on the \"`+`\" icon at the top-right of any GitHub page, and select \"`New organization`\" from the menu.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:16
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
".The \"`New organization`\" menu item\n"
"image::images/neworg.png[The âNew organizationâ menu item]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:19
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"First you'll need to name your organization and provide an email address for a main point of contact for the group.\n"
"Then you can invite other users to be co-owners of the account if you want to.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:22
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Follow these steps and you'll soon be the owner of a brand-new organization.\n"
"Like personal accounts, organizations are free if everything you plan to store there will be open source.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:26
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"As an owner in an organization, when you fork a repository, you'll have the choice of forking it to your organization's namespace.\n"
"When you create new repositories you can create them either under your personal account or under any of the organizations that you are an owner in.\n"
"You also automatically \"`watch`\" any new repository created under these organizations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:29
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Just like in <<_personal_avatar>>, you can upload an avatar for your organization to personalize it a bit.\n"
"Also just like personal accounts, you have a landing page for the organization that lists all of your repositories and can be viewed by other people.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now let's cover some of the things that are a bit different with an organizational account.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Teams\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "Organizations are associated with individual people by way of teams, which are simply a grouping of individual user accounts and repositories within the organization and what kind of access those people have in those repositories.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:39
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For example, say your company has three repositories: `frontend`, `backend`, and `deployscripts`.\n"
"You'd want your HTML/CSS/JavaScript developers to have access to `frontend` and maybe `backend`, and your Operations people to have access to `backend` and `deployscripts`.\n"
"Teams make this easy, without having to manage the collaborators for every individual repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:41
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Organization page shows you a simple dashboard of all the repositories, users and teams that are under this organization.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:45
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_org_page]]\n"
".The Organization page\n"
"image::images/orgs-01-page.png[The Organization page]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:50
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To manage your Teams, you can click on the Teams sidebar on the right hand side of the page in <<_org_page>>.\n"
"This will bring you to a page you can use to add members to the team, add repositories to the team or manage the settings and access control levels for the team.\n"
"Each team can have read only, read/write or administrative access to the repositories.\n"
"You can change that level by clicking the \"`Settings`\" button in <<_team_page>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_team_page]]\n"
".The Team page\n"
"image::images/orgs-02-teams.png[The Team page]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "When you invite someone to a team, they will get an email letting them know they've been invited.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:59
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Additionally, team `@mentions` (such as `@acmecorp/frontend`) work much the same as they do with individual users, except that *all* members of the team are then subscribed to the thread.\n"
"This is useful if you want the attention from someone on a team, but you don't know exactly who to ask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:62
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A user can belong to any number of teams, so don't limit yourself to only access-control teams.\n"
"Special-interest teams like `ux`, `css`, or `refactoring` are useful for certain kinds of questions, and others like `legal` and `colorblind` for an entirely different kind.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Audit Log\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:67
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Organizations also give owners access to all the information about what went on under the organization.\n"
"You can go to the 'Audit Log' tab and see what events have happened at an organization level, who did them and where in the world they were done.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:71
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_the_audit_log]]\n"
".The Audit log\n"
"image::images/orgs-03-audit.png[The Audit log]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/4-managing-organization.asc:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can also filter down to specific types of events, specific places or specific people.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "=== Scripting GitHub\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:4
#, no-wrap
msgid "So now we've covered all of the major features and workflows of GitHub, but any large group or project will have customizations they may want to make or external services they may want to integrate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:7
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Luckily for us, GitHub is really quite hackable in many ways.\n"
"In this section we'll cover how to use the GitHub hooks system and its API to make GitHub work how we want it to.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Services and Hooks\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "The Hooks and Services section of GitHub repository administration is the easiest way to have GitHub interact with external systems.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:13
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Services\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:17
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"First we'll take a look at Services.\n"
"Both the Hooks and Services integrations can be found in the Settings section of your repository, where we previously looked at adding Collaborators and changing the default branch of your project.\n"
"Under the \"`Webhooks and Services`\" tab you will see something like <<_services_hooks>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:21
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_services_hooks]]\n"
".Services and Hooks configuration section\n"
"image::images/scripting-01-services.png[Services and hooks]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:26
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are dozens of services you can choose from, most of them integrations into other commercial and open source systems.\n"
"Most of them are for Continuous Integration services, bug and issue trackers, chat room systems and documentation systems.\n"
"We'll walk through setting up a very simple one, the Email hook.\n"
"If you choose \"`email`\" from the \"`Add Service`\" dropdown, you'll get a configuration screen like <<_service_config>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:30
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_service_config]]\n"
".Email service configuration\n"
"image::images/scripting-02-email-service.png[Email service]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:33
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this case, if we hit the \"`Add service`\" button, the email address we specified will get an email every time someone pushes to the repository.\n"
"Services can listen for lots of different types of events, but most only listen for push events and then do something with that data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:36
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If there is a system you are using that you would like to integrate with GitHub, you should check here to see if there is an existing service integration available.\n"
"For example, if you're using Jenkins to run tests on your codebase, you can enable the Jenkins builtin service integration to kick off a test run every time someone pushes to your repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "===== Hooks\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:42
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you need something more specific or you want to integrate with a service or site that is not included in this list, you can instead use the more generic hooks system.\n"
"GitHub repository hooks are pretty simple.\n"
"You specify a URL and GitHub will post an HTTP payload to that URL on any event you want.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:44
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generally the way this works is you can setup a small web service to listen for a GitHub hook payload and then do something with the data when it is received.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:47
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To enable a hook, you click the \"`Add webhook`\" button in <<_services_hooks>>.\n"
"This will bring you to a page that looks like <<_web_hook>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:51
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_web_hook]]\n"
".Web hook configuration\n"
"image::images/scripting-03-webhook.png[Web hook]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:55
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The configuration for a web hook is pretty simple.\n"
"In most cases you simply enter a URL and a secret key and hit \"`Add webhook`\".\n"
"There are a few options for which events you want GitHub to send you a payload for -- the default is to only get a payload for the `push` event, when someone pushes new code to any branch of your repository.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:58
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's see a small example of a web service you may set up to handle a web hook.\n"
"We'll use the Ruby web framework Sinatra since it's fairly concise and you should be able to easily see what we're doing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:61
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Let's say we want to get an email if a specific person pushes to a specific branch of our project modifying a specific file.\n"
"We could fairly easily do that with code like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:63
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:237
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[source,ruby]\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:67
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"require 'sinatra'\n"
"require 'json'\n"
"require 'mail'\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"post '/payload' do\n"
"  push = JSON.parse(request.body.read) # parse the JSON\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:74
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  # gather the data we're looking for\n"
"  pusher = push[\"pusher\"][\"name\"]\n"
"  branch = push[\"ref\"]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:80
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  # get a list of all the files touched\n"
"  files = push[\"commits\"].map do |commit|\n"
"    commit['added'] + commit['modified'] + commit['removed']\n"
"  end\n"
"  files = files.flatten.uniq\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:85
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  # check for our criteria\n"
"  if pusher == 'schacon' &&\n"
"     branch == 'ref/heads/special-branch' &&\n"
"     files.include?('special-file.txt')\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:94
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Mail.deliver do\n"
"      from     'tchacon@example.com'\n"
"      to       'tchacon@example.com'\n"
"      subject  'Scott Changed the File'\n"
"      body     \"ALARM\"\n"
"    end\n"
"  end\n"
"end\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:98
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Here we're taking the JSON payload that GitHub delivers us and looking up who pushed it, what branch they pushed to and what files were touched in all the commits that were pushed.\n"
"Then we check that against our criteria and send an email if it matches.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:103
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In order to develop and test something like this, you have a nice developer console in the same screen where you set the hook up.\n"
"You can see the last few deliveries that GitHub has tried to make for that webhook.\n"
"For each hook you can dig down into when it was delivered, if it was successful and the body and headers for both the request and the response.\n"
"This makes it incredibly easy to test and debug your hooks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:107
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_web_hook_debug]]\n"
".Web hook debugging information\n"
"image::images/scripting-04-webhook-debug.png[Webhook debug]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:109
#, no-wrap
msgid "The other great feature of this is that you can redeliver any of the payloads to test your service easily.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:111
#, no-wrap
msgid "For more information on how to write webhooks and all the different event types you can listen for, go to the GitHub Developer documentation at https://developer.github.com/webhooks/[].\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:113
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== The GitHub API\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"(((GitHub, API)))\n"
"Services and hooks give you a way to receive push notifications about events that happen on your repositories, but what if you need more information about these events?\n"
"What if you need to automate something like adding collaborators or labeling issues?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:121
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This is where the GitHub API comes in handy.\n"
"GitHub has tons of API endpoints for doing nearly anything you can do on the website in an automated fashion.\n"
"In this section we'll learn how to authenticate and connect to the API, how to comment on an issue and how to change the status of a Pull Request through the API.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:123
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Basic Usage\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The most basic thing you can do is a simple GET request on an endpoint that doesn't require authentication.\n"
"This could be a user or read-only information on an open source project.\n"
"For example, if we want to know more about a user named \"`schacon`\", we can run something like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:129
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:148
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:197
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[source,javascript]\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:142
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ curl https://api.github.com/users/schacon\n"
"{\n"
"  \"login\": \"schacon\",\n"
"  \"id\": 70,\n"
"  \"avatar_url\": \"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/70\",\n"
"# â¦\n"
"  \"name\": \"Scott Chacon\",\n"
"  \"company\": \"GitHub\",\n"
"  \"following\": 19,\n"
"  \"created_at\": \"2008-01-27T17:19:28Z\",\n"
"  \"updated_at\": \"2014-06-10T02:37:23Z\"\n"
"}\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:146
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are tons of endpoints like this to get information about organizations, projects, issues, commits -- just about anything you can publicly see on GitHub.\n"
"You can even use the API to render arbitrary Markdown or find a `.gitignore` template.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:153
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ curl https://api.github.com/gitignore/templates/Java\n"
"{\n"
"  \"name\": \"Java\",\n"
"  \"source\": \"*.class\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:156
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Mobile Tools for Java (J2ME)\n"
".mtj.tmp/\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:161
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Package Files #\n"
"*.jar\n"
"*.war\n"
"*.ear\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:166
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# virtual machine crash logs, see https://www.java.com/en/download/help/error_hotspot.xml\n"
"hs_err_pid*\n"
"\"\n"
"}\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:170
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Commenting on an Issue\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:172
#, no-wrap
msgid "However, if you want to do an action on the website such as comment on an Issue or Pull Request or if you want to view or interact with private content, you'll need to authenticate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:176
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are several ways to authenticate.\n"
"You can use basic authentication with just your username and password, but generally it's a better idea to use a personal access token.\n"
"You can generate this from the \"`Applications`\" tab of your settings page.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:180
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_access_token]]\n"
".Generate your access token from the \"`Applications`\" tab of your settings page\n"
"image::images/scripting-05-access-token.png[Access Token]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:183
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"It will ask you which scopes you want for this token and a description.\n"
"Make sure to use a good description so you feel comfortable removing the token when your script or application is no longer used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:187
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GitHub will only show you the token once, so be sure to copy it.\n"
"You can now use this to authenticate in your script instead of using a username and password.\n"
"This is nice because you can limit the scope of what you want to do and the token is revocable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:191
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"This also has the added advantage of increasing your rate limit.\n"
"Without authenticating, you will be limited to 60 requests per hour.\n"
"If you authenticate you can make up to 5,000 requests per hour.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:195
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"So let's use it to make a comment on one of our issues.\n"
"Let's say we want to leave a comment on a specific issue, Issue #6.\n"
"To do so we have to do an HTTP POST request to `repos/<user>/<repo>/issues/<num>/comments` with the token we just generated as an Authorization header.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:216
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ curl -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n"
"       -H \"Authorization: token TOKEN\" \\\n"
"       --data '{\"body\":\"A new comment, :+1:\"}' \\\n"
"       https://api.github.com/repos/schacon/blink/issues/6/comments\n"
"{\n"
"  \"id\": 58322100,\n"
"  \"html_url\": \"https://github.com/schacon/blink/issues/6#issuecomment-58322100\",\n"
"  ...\n"
"  \"user\": {\n"
"    \"login\": \"tonychacon\",\n"
"    \"id\": 7874698,\n"
"    \"avatar_url\": \"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/7874698?v=2\",\n"
"    \"type\": \"User\",\n"
"  },\n"
"  \"created_at\": \"2014-10-08T07:48:19Z\",\n"
"  \"updated_at\": \"2014-10-08T07:48:19Z\",\n"
"  \"body\": \"A new comment, :+1:\"\n"
"}\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:219
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now if you go to that issue, you can see the comment that we just successfully posted as in <<_api_comment>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:223
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_api_comment]]\n"
".A comment posted from the GitHub API\n"
"image::images/scripting-06-comment.png[API Comment]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:225
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can use the API to do just about anything you can do on the website -- creating and setting milestones, assigning people to Issues and Pull Requests, creating and changing labels, accessing commit data, creating new commits and branches, opening, closing or merging Pull Requests, creating and editing teams, commenting on lines of code in a Pull Request, searching the site and on and on.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:227
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Changing the Status of a Pull Request\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:230
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There is one final example we'll look at since it's really useful if you're working with Pull Requests.\n"
"Each commit can have one or more statuses associated with it and there is an API to add and query that status.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:233
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Most of the Continuous Integration and testing services make use of this API to react to pushes by testing the code that was pushed, and then report back if that commit has passed all the tests.\n"
"You could also use this to check if the commit message is properly formatted, if the submitter followed all your contribution guidelines, if the commit was validly signed -- any number of things.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:235
#, no-wrap
msgid "Let's say you set up a webhook on your repository that hits a small web service that checks for a `Signed-off-by` string in the commit message.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:241
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"require 'httparty'\n"
"require 'sinatra'\n"
"require 'json'\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:245
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"post '/payload' do\n"
"  push = JSON.parse(request.body.read) # parse the JSON\n"
"  repo_name = push['repository']['full_name']\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:248
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  # look through each commit message\n"
"  push[\"commits\"].each do |commit|\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:257
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # look for a Signed-off-by string\n"
"    if /Signed-off-by/.match commit['message']\n"
"      state = 'success'\n"
"      description = 'Successfully signed off!'\n"
"    else\n"
"      state = 'failure'\n"
"      description = 'No signoff found.'\n"
"    end\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:261
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # post status to GitHub\n"
"    sha = commit[\"id\"]\n"
"    status_url = \"https://api.github.com/repos/#{repo_name}/statuses/#{sha}\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:277
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    status = {\n"
"      \"state\"       => state,\n"
"      \"description\" => description,\n"
"      \"target_url\"  => \"http://example.com/how-to-signoff\",\n"
"      \"context\"     => \"validate/signoff\"\n"
"    }\n"
"    HTTParty.post(status_url,\n"
"      :body => status.to_json,\n"
"      :headers => {\n"
"        'Content-Type'  => 'application/json',\n"
"        'User-Agent'    => 'tonychacon/signoff',\n"
"        'Authorization' => \"token #{ENV['TOKEN']}\" }\n"
"    )\n"
"  end\n"
"end\n"
"----\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:281
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Hopefully this is fairly simple to follow.\n"
"In this web hook handler we look through each commit that was just pushed, we look for the string 'Signed-off-by' in the commit message and finally we POST via HTTP to the `/repos/<user>/<repo>/statuses/<commit_sha>` API endpoint with the status.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:284
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In this case you can send a state ('success', 'failure', 'error'), a description of what happened, a target URL the user can go to for more information and a \"`context`\" in case there are multiple statuses for a single commit.\n"
"For example, a testing service may provide a status and a validation service like this may also provide a status -- the \"`context`\" field is how they're differentiated.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:286
#, no-wrap
msgid "If someone opens a new Pull Request on GitHub and this hook is set up, you may see something like <<_commit_status>>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:290
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[[_commit_status]]\n"
".Commit status via the API\n"
"image::images/scripting-07-status.png[Commit status]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:294
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can now see a little green check mark next to the commit that has a \"`Signed-off-by`\" string in the message and a red cross through the one where the author forgot to sign off.\n"
"You can also see that the Pull Request takes the status of the last commit on the branch and warns you if it is a failure.\n"
"This is really useful if you're using this API for test results so you don't accidentally merge something where the last commit is failing tests.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:296
#, no-wrap
msgid "==== Octokit\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:300
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Though we've been doing nearly everything through `curl` and simple HTTP requests in these examples, several open-source libraries exist that make this API available in a more idiomatic way.\n"
"At the time of this writing, the supported languages include Go, Objective-C, Ruby, and .NET.\n"
"Check out https://github.com/octokit[] for more information on these, as they handle much of the HTTP for you.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: book/06-github/sections/5-scripting.asc:302
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Hopefully these tools can help you customize and modify GitHub to work better for your specific workflows.\n"
"For complete documentation on the entire API as well as guides for common tasks, check out https://developer.github.com[].\n"
msgstr ""
